Prior to the last recession, Nortel laid of 60,000 of their 90,000
employees.  those people FELT the recession. Not only did they lose
their jobs, but available jobs in their field were nonexistent.
Although most people were aware of the recession, most did not &quot;feel&quot;
the recession.  If you look at figure #1 in http://www.nber.org/cycles/november2001 ,
you will see that employment didn't really go down much in the
recession.

HOWEVER, recession or no recession, YOUR job loss is significant for
YOU.  The question is not how do you plan for a recession, the
question is how do you plan for job loss.  Even if there is the
unlikely scenario of there being no recession in your lifetime, you
WILL lose your job at least once.

Issue #1, save one of every four paychecks.  Put the max contribution
in a ROTH IRA.  Put the rest in a portfolio with a low cost investment
company, such as Fidelity or Vanguard.  Don't worry about stock market
crashes.  Even if you had invested your money the day BEFORE the 1987
crash, it would still be up 400% today.

Issue #2:  After you have gotten used to saving 25%, then cut your
spending even more and save 2 paychecks out of very 4.  This is a lot
easier to start right after college when you are used to living on
virtually nothing.  As you get older &amp; get accustomed to spending, it
gets harder.  START NOW.

Saving 50% will do two things. It will get you used to living on less
and it will get you saving for your retirement. SO, when you do
retire, you will need less.

Issue #3: Divorce your health care from your employer.  Bargain with
your employer.  It costs money for him to insure you.  Tell him you
want a higher salary instead of health insurance.  Get a high
deductible insurance while you are young an KEEP IT. Get a Health
Savings Account (HSA).  Continue adding to your HSA THEN increase your
deductible even more.  Calculate the difference between what you pay
for insurance and what your employer would have had to pay.  Put that
amount in a separate stock fund so you can see your health savings
first hand.

By doing this, you will not have to worry about health care between
jobs.  You will also be preparing yourself for health insurance during
your retirement.

Before you know it, your fears of recession will have disappeared and
you will be retired at an early age.
