There is no industry easier to get into than the industry that only needs
a seat, a desk, and a computer (and, of course, that can be exported to
India). You don't need a factory, machines, inventory, distribution
networks, cust service can be much smaller, product returns &amp; warranty
handling not needed, etc.

I've been noticing all manner of pure crap coming out. Schools of all
manner are offering &quot;travel education packages&quot; (go to all manner of
places, usually Europe/Russia/etc on a package [good deal, they organize a
package discount, split the discount between you and them, all on the
cheap). AARP for a long time took your membership and then used that to
sollicit more donations and passed your name on to life insurance,
x-insurance companies as part of some &quot;AARP&quot; program. Now, my electric
company (after the deregulation price increases) is starting up a
&quot;consumer discount&quot; program where you get a plastic card that gives you
some dinky discount and now its free, but once it gets rolling, its going
to probably come out of what they bill you. I'm seeing all kinds of this
NEW business being &quot;spun out of&quot; the existing business and its all
expanded red tape. Wife still does best with old fashioned paper coupons
from the newspapers (no names, no databases, no privacy concerns, no ID
theft, etc.). Her Alma Matter and mine, too, are bombarding us with at
least one, sometimes two sollicitations per week now to donate to the
Alumni fund, organize a bequest, buy in on these &quot;educational travel&quot;
packages, etc. Even my bank sent out a promotional to get loans for a
higher degree and, of course, splashed a statement about &quot;college grads
make ave $43,000&quot; and the fine print suggested that they cherry-picked the
data from a small number of majors to get that number (and didn't say
squat about all those who finish their programs and don't get jobs in
those subjects, etc.).

The CC business is one of the most lucrative out there. High ROI even
after all the writeoffs. And, what is the bottom line? Money...flowing
from the less rich (the poor) to the more rich (the rich). But, all the
advertising makes it sound like its &quot;easy&quot; and &quot;good&quot; and &quot;healthy&quot; to go
into debt, let the parasites let you do the work and THEY get &quot;rent&quot;.

And, of course, you'd never hear any politician get up and say &quot;Hey,
people, you're just digging yourself into debt...how about pay off that
debt and save yourself a ton of money over your lifetime!&quot;

